://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Body_measures_SVG.svg/=
langenglish-250px-Body_measures_SVG.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"25=
0" height=3D"176" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-fi=
le-height=3D"361"></a><figcaption>Examples of body measurements used for th=
e sizing of clothes</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Clothing sizes</b> are the sizes with which <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Garment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Garment">garments</=
a> sold <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ready-to-wear" title=3D"Re=
ady-to-wear">off-the-shelf</a> are labeled. Sizing systems vary based on th=
e country and the type of garment, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Dress_(garment)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dress (garment)">d=
resses</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top_(clothing)" title=
=3D"Top (clothing)">tops</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skir=
t" title=3D"Skirt">skirts</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Trousers" title=3D"Trousers">trousers</a>. There are three approaches:
</p>
<ul><li><b>Body dimensions</b>: The label states the range of body measurem=
ents for which the product was designed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#cite_note-1=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> (For example: bike helmet label stating "head girth: 56=E2=80=
=9360 cm".)</li>
<li><b>Product dimensions</b>: The label states characteristic dimensions o=
f the product. (For example: jeans label stating inner leg length of the je=
ans in centimetres or inches (not inner leg measurement of the intended wea=
rer).)</li>
<li><b>Ad hoc sizes</b>: The label states a size number or code with no obv=
ious relationship to any measurement. (For example: Size 12, XL.) Children'=
s clothes sizes are sometimes described by the age of the child, or, for in=
fants, the weight.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
lothing_sizes#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Traditionally, clothes have been labelled using many different ad hoc si=
ze systems, which has resulted in varying sizing methods between different =
manufacturers made for different countries due to changing demographics and=
 increasing rates of obesity, a phenomenon known as <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Vanity_sizing" title=3D"Vanity sizing">vanity sizing</a>.=
 This results in country-specific and vendor-specific labels incurring addi=
tional costs, and can make <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interne=
t_shop" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Internet shop">internet</a> or <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mail_order" title=3D"Mail order">mail o=
rder</a> difficult. Some new standards for clothing sizes being developed a=
re therefore based on body dimensions, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/EN_13402" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"EN 13402">EN 1340=
2</a> "Size designation of clothes".
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History_of_standard_clothin=
g_sizes">History of standard clothing sizes</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DClothing_sizes&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History of standard clothing sizes"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Before the invention of standardized clothing sizes in the early 1800s, =
all clothing was made to fit individuals by either <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Tailor" title=3D"Tailor">tailors</a> or makers of clothing=
 in their homes. Then garment makers noticed that the range of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_body" title=3D"Human body">human body</a=
> dimensions was relatively small (for their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Demographic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Demographic">demogra=
phic</a>). Because of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drape" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Drape">drape</a> and ease of the fabric, not =
all measurements are required to obtain a well-fitting apparel in most styl=
es. Sizes were based on:
</p>
<ul><li><b>Horizontal torso measurements</b>, which include the neck circum=
ference, the shoulder width, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
ustline" title=3D"Bustline">bustline measurements</a> =E2=80=93 over-bust c=
ircumference, the full bust circumference, the bust-point separation, and t=
he under-bust (rib-cage) circumference =E2=80=93 the natural <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waistline_(clothing)" title=3D"Waistline (clothi=
ng)">waist circumference</a>, the upper hip circumference and the lower hip=
 circumference.</li>
<li><b>Vertical torso measurements</b>, which include the back (neck-waist)=
 length, the shoulder-waist length (not the same as the back length, due to=
 the slope of the shoulder), the bust-shoulder length, the bust-waist lengt=
h, and the two hip-waist lengths.</li>
<li><b>Sleeve measurements</b>, which include the under-arm and over-arm le=
ngths, the fore-arm length, the wrist circumference and the biceps circumfe=
rence.</li></ul>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Pit-to-pit_measurement"></span><i>Pit-to-pi=
t measurement</i> is not a tailoring measurement, but a finished garment me=
asure, used in the second-hand internet marketplace, generally the straight=
 line measure across the garment, laid flat, at the bottom of the armpits.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-stcyrvintage/size-guide_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#cite_note-stcyrvintage/siz=
e-guide-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-nimisski/pit-to-pit_5-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#cite_not=
e-nimisski/pit-to-pit-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3sixteen/measuring-=
guide-tops_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Clothing_sizes#cite_note-3sixteen/measuring-guide-tops-6"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-fritidsklader/pit-to-pit_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
