ng=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"237" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"709" data-file-height=3D"673"></a><figcaption>Clothes-size labe=
l with EN&nbsp;13402-3 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pictogram" =
title=3D"Pictogram">pictogram</a> and body dimensions in centimetres (found=
 on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High-visibility_clothing" ti=
tle=3D"High-visibility clothing">high-visibility</a> jacket sold in the Uni=
ted Kingdom).</figcaption></figure>
<ul><li>BS 3666:1982 Specification for size designation of women's wear</li=
>
<li>BS 6185:1982 Specification for size designation of men's wear</li></ul>
<p>BS 3666:1982, the standard for women's clothing, is rarely followed by m=
anufacturers as it defines sizes in terms of hip and bust measurements only=
 within a limited range. This has resulted in variations between manufactur=
ers and a tendency towards <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vanity_=
sizing" title=3D"Vanity sizing">vanity sizing</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#c=
ite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Yugoslavian_standards">Yugo=
slavian standards</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DClothing_sizes&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Yugoslavian standards"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Former_Yugoslavia"></span><span class=3D"an=
chor" id=3D"JUS"></span>
Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, North Macedonia and Serbia still=
 use the JUS (F.G0.001 1979, F.G0.002 1979, F.G0.003 1979) standards develo=
ped in the former <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yugoslavia" titl=
e=3D"Yugoslavia">Yugoslavia</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#cite_note-10"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> In addition to typical girth measurements clothing is also marked t=
o identify which of 5 height bands: X-Short, Short, Medium, Tall, X-Tall, a=
nd body types: Slim, Normal, or Full, it is designed to fit.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"American_standards">America=
n standards</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Clothing_sizes&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: A=
merican standards"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"North_America"></span>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"US_standards">US standards<=
/h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DClothing_siz=
es&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: US standards"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"United_States"></span><span class=3D"anchor=
" id=3D"CS"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"PS"></span><span class=3D"a=
nchor" id=3D"ASTM"></span>
</p>
<ul><li>CS-151-50 - Infants, Babies, Toddlers and Children's clothing</li>
<li>CS 215-58 - Women's Clothing (1958)</li>
<li>PS 36-70 - Boys Clothing (1971)</li>
<li>PS 42-70 =E2=80=93 Women's Clothing (1971)</li>
<li>PS 45-71 - Young Men's clothing</li>
<li>PS 54-72 - Girls Clothing</li>
<li>ASTM D5585-95 (2001)</li>
<li>ASTM D6829-02 (2008)</li>
<li>ASTM D5585-11 (2011) (withdrawn, 2020)</li>
<li>ASTM D6240-98</li>
<li>ASTM D6960-04 =E2=80=93 Women's Plus sizes (2004)</li></ul>
<p>There is no mandatory clothing size or labeling standard in the US, thou=
gh a series of voluntary standards have been in place since the 1930s. The =
US government, however, did attempt to establish a system for women's cloth=
ing in 1958 when the National Bureau of Standards published <i>Body Measure=
ments for the Sizing of Women's Patterns and Apparel</i>. The guidelines we=
re made a commercial standard and were even updated in 1970. But the guide =
was eventually degraded to a voluntary standard until it was abolished alto=
gether in 1983.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Private o=
rganization <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASTM_International" ti=
tle=3D"ASTM International">ASTM International</a> started to release its ow=
n recommended size carts in the 1990s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-time_12-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#cite=
_note-time-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Since then, the common US misses sizes have not had stable dimension=
s. Clothing brands and manufacturers size their products according to their=
 preferences.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-time_12-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_sizes#cite_note-time-12"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 For example, the dimensions of two size 10 dresses from different companie=
s, or even from the same company, may have grossly different dimensions; an=
d both are almost certainly larger than the size 10 dimensions described in=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_standard_clothing_size" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"US standard clothing size">US standard</a>. <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vanity_sizing" title=3D"Vanity sizin=
g">Vanity sizing</a> may be partly responsible for this deviation (which be=
gan in earnest in the 1980s).
</p>
